      "title": "Module 1 — Why appetite sometimes rises",
      "text": "Two honest reasons people may eat more after quitting. First, your senses recover — food genuinely tastes and smells better, which can make eating more appealing. That's a good sign, your body healing, even if it's a little inconvenient. Second, and more importantly, there's a psychological trap: reaching for food as a substitute for the cigarette. This is the one to watch. When a craving or an old trigger fires and you stuff something in your mouth to fill the void, you're treating the cigarette as a loss that needs replacing — and that belief, not the food itself, is the real problem.\n\nHere's the key: the empty feeling of a nicotine craving is not hunger, and food won't satisfy it. If anything, snacking when you're not hungry keeps you focused on the void and prolongs the sense that you've given something up. You haven't given anything up — so there's nothing to fill."
